Let's use some strings on $7$ characters of $0$ and $1$ to indicate the members of each set. Then the minimally intersecting (	extit{MI}) condition is satisfied if there exists exactly one $1$ in each row and column but different strings for $A,B,$ and $C$ only differ in indexes of their $0$'s. In other words, if the entries in each column are labeled from $1$ to $7$, we must have $a_{11}
eq a_{12}
eq a_{13}$, $a_{21}
eq a_{22}
eq a_{23}$, and so on, where $a_{ij}=	ext{character}$ at the $i^{	ext{th}}$ row and $j^{	ext{th}}$ column. The total number of ways this can be done is $6\cdot5\cdot4\cdot3\cdot2\cdot1\cdot1=720$. Since there are $2^7=128$ ways to create MI triplets for each $7$ characters, we divide $720$ by $128$ and get the answer $	extbf{112}$ modulo $1000$. </think>

